04245nam a22007095i 9780814784372DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t19991999nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147843727 a10.18574/nyu/97808147843722doi  a(DE-B1597)548618  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF9329b.T37 1999eb 7aLAW0430002bisacsh04a345.73/025322211 aTaslitz, Andrew E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRape and the Culture of the Courtroom /cAndrew E. Taslitz. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical America ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote to the Reader -- tIntroduction -- tPart I Patriarchal Stories -- t1 Cultural Rape Narratives -- t2 Cultural Rape Narratives in the Courtroom -- t3 A Fair Fight -- tPart II Lawyers’ Language in the Courtroom -- t4 Gendered Language -- t5 Lawyers’ Language and the Rape Trial -- tPart III Feminist Evidence Law -- t6 Market Failure -- t7 Group Voices -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRape law reform has been a stunning failure. Defense lawyers persist in emphasizing victims' characters over defendants' behavior. Reform's goals of increasing rape report and conviction rates have generally not been achieved. In Rape and the Culture of the Courtroom, Andrew Taslitz locates the cause of rape reform failure in the language lawyers use, and the cultural stories upon which they draw to dominate rape victims in the courtroom. Cultural stories about rape, Taslitz argues, such as the provocatively dressed woman "asking for it," are at the root of many unconscious prejudices that determine jury views. He connects these stories with real-life examples, such as the Mike Tyson and Glen Ridge rape trials, to show how rape stereotypes are used by defense lawyers to gain acquittals for their clients. Building on Deborah Tannen's pathbreaking research on the differences between male and female speech, Taslitz also demonstrates how word choice, tone, and other lawyers' linguistic tactics work to undermine the confidence and the credibility of the victim, weakening her voice during the trial. Taslitz provides politically realistic reform proposals, consistent with feminist theories of justice, which promise to improve both the adversary system in general and the way that the system handles rape cases.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aAdversary system (Law)zUnited States. 0aLaw reformzUnited States. 0aRapezUnited States. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814784372423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814784372/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK